{
  "episode": 55,
  "summary": "Practices past participle adjectives with estar, introduces should have (debería haber) and could have (podría haber) structures, and teaches several irregular past participles: roto (romper), muerto (morir), abierto (abrir), dicho (decir), hecho (hacer). Also covers the f-to-silent-h sound change between English and Spanish.",
  "teachings": [
    {
      "conceptSlug": "past-participle-as-adjective",
      "conceptName": "Past participle as adjective",
      "category": "Grammar",
      "role": "practiced",
      "summary": "Continued practice using past participles as adjectives with estar. Some like complicado can go with either ser or estar.",
      "rule": null,
      "examples": [
        {"spanish": "Está cancelado", "english": "It is cancelled"},
        {"spanish": "Está cancelada", "english": "It is cancelled (la fiesta)"},
        {"spanish": "Se ha complicado", "english": "It has got complicated"},
        {"spanish": "Es complicado", "english": "It is complicated (ser)"},
        {"spanish": "Está complicado", "english": "It is complicated (estar)"}
      ],
      "notes": "Complicado can go with either ser or estar. Most participle adjectives tend toward estar."
